This isn't really garbage, it's just brutally self-conscious. You set out a moody, atmospheric scene, but then you kept telling us how it was supposed to make us feel rather than just letting it make us feel that way. I can't come up with a good syntax to edit it without making it look like a clusterfuck, so bear with me

First off, grammar. Sentence one is a hell of a run-on. The first half could be correct with some word swaps for tense agreement, but it would read better piecemeal anyway. How about:

>The howling wind and rain came down hard on Ariyah's bedroom window. Grey, moody clouds blanketed the culdesac skyline, and the sound of the pitter patter of rain became the soundtrack to her blue mood. She was deep in thought. Her human friend was moving away tomorrow. He'd always been too scared to make it more than just friends between them, even though there was an unspoken connection. <Ariyah softly consoles herself, talking to her condensated window.>
"Stupid Anon, moving away leaving me here in this dump of a town all by myself."

>Broke the sentence between "window" and "thick". We have a clear, well-rounded subject and predicate, and the rest of the sentence is better suited to compounding than the beginning.
>Recompounded the second half of the sentence with a comma between "skyline" and "and". Started a new sentence again with "deep in thought".
>Cut redundancies out of the bits about the human friend and broke the sentence in a few places.]
>Edited some tense agreement. If you're writing in past, stick to past and be consistent. Greentext is traditionally written in present tense, but that isn't really a must.
>Referring to the carrot-wrapped text: you need to decide if you're greentexting or not. This is a very awkward sentence in longform, but serves greentext bullet-list-action syntax. If so, give it a meme arrow and a new line all it's own.

Next, content. "Show, don't tell" is very handy advice, and it looks like you've taken it. The biggest problem is you're still telling. If you're going to prompt us with the environment, don't tell us what it's supposed to prompt us with, or even how the character herself feels. You already told us how she feels with the clouds. Any other day that rain might be beautiful to her instead of melancholy, and the fact that it's melancholy tells us all we need to know.
Refer to pic related. The author DID just mean that the drapes were fucking blue, but he made the drapes blue for a reason. They don't represent shit, but the he knows how people react to the color blue, particularly when it's described in a certain way. This sort of thing isn't about showing that you're part of some exclusive club, though some teachers make it sound that way. Let's edit some more.

>The howling wind and rain came down hard on Ariyah's bedroom window. Thick, water-leaden clouds blanketed the culdesac skyline, and the pitter patter of rain droned on in the back of her mind like white noise.


>Eliminated "moody". We don't need to be told how to feel. Added "thick" and swapped "gray" for water-leaden so we can be a little more specific to make up for the loss of "moody". Really I would reccomend a metaphor here as you could say a lot more with a lot less. If you've ever had a lead apron on for an X-ray, maybe try describing the clouds like that.
>Eliminated "the sound of" before "pitter patter". Redundant.
>Swapped the "soundtrack" description for something that says a little more about how (to my best judgement) she feels. The patter of rain tends to have a chaotic pattern, but it's short and repeats consistently. That offers a pretty good symbolism relationship, as that's kind of what we see her thoughts doing too: lashing out randomly in frustration, but treading the same points over and over again. To my ear, "white noise" prompts this more effectively.
